2013.a.Solution:
The reduced mass $m$ of the positronium is given by $\frac{1}{m}=\frac{1}{m_{e}}+\frac{1}{m_{e}}$, i.e., $m=m_{e} / 2$. Its use in the formulas gives

$$
\begin{aligned}
E_{0} &=\frac{-e^{2}}{2 a_{0}}=-\frac{m c^{2}}{2}\left(\frac{e^{2}}{\hbar c}\right)^{2}=\frac{-0.51 \times 10^{6}}{4 \times 137^{2}}=-6.8 \mathrm{eV} \\
a_{0} &=1.05 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~cm}
\end{aligned}
$$

2013.b.Solution:
The reduced mass $m$ of the positronium is given by $\frac{1}{m}=\frac{1}{m_{e}}+\frac{1}{m_{e}}$, i.e., $m=m_{e} / 2$. Its use in the formulas gives

$$
\begin{aligned}
E_{0} &=\frac{-e^{2}}{2 a_{0}}=-\frac{m c^{2}}{2}\left(\frac{e^{2}}{\hbar c}\right)^{2}=\frac{-0.51 \times 10^{6}}{4 \times 137^{2}}=-6.8 \mathrm{eV} \\
a_{0} &=1.05 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~cm}
\end{aligned}
$$The degeneracy of the positronium ground state is 4. Denote the positron by 1 and the electron by 2 , and let the spin eigenstates in the $z$ direction of a single particle be $\alpha$ and $\beta$, corresponding to eigenvalues $\hbar / 2$ and $-\hbar / 2$ respectively. Then the ground eigenstates with definite total spin $S=s_{1}+s_{2}$ and $z$-component of the total spin $S_{z}=s_{1 z}+s_{2 z}$ are

$$
\begin{array}{lll}
\alpha(1) \alpha(2), & S=\hbar, & S_{z}=\hbar . \\
\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}[\alpha(1) \beta(2)+\beta(1) \alpha(2)], & S=\hbar, & S_{z}=0 . \\
\beta(1) \beta(2), & S=\hbar, & S_{z}=-\hbar . \\
\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}[\alpha(1) \beta(2)-\beta(1) \alpha(2)], & S=0, & S_{z}=0 .
\end{array}
$$

2013.c.Solution:
The reduced mass $m$ of the positronium is given by $\frac{1}{m}=\frac{1}{m_{e}}+\frac{1}{m_{e}}$, i.e., $m=m_{e} / 2$. Its use in the formulas gives

$$
\begin{aligned}
E_{0} &=\frac{-e^{2}}{2 a_{0}}=-\frac{m c^{2}}{2}\left(\frac{e^{2}}{\hbar c}\right)^{2}=\frac{-0.51 \times 10^{6}}{4 \times 137^{2}}=-6.8 \mathrm{eV} \\
a_{0} &=1.05 \times 10^{-8} \mathrm{~cm}
\end{aligned}
$$The degeneracy of the positronium ground state is 4. Denote the positron by 1 and the electron by 2 , and let the spin eigenstates in the $z$ direction of a single particle be $\alpha$ and $\beta$, corresponding to eigenvalues $\hbar / 2$ and $-\hbar / 2$ respectively. Then the ground eigenstates with definite total spin $S=s_{1}+s_{2}$ and $z$-component of the total spin $S_{z}=s_{1 z}+s_{2 z}$ are

$$
\begin{array}{lll}
\alpha(1) \alpha(2), & S=\hbar, & S_{z}=\hbar . \\
\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}[\alpha(1) \beta(2)+\beta(1) \alpha(2)], & S=\hbar, & S_{z}=0 . \\
\beta(1) \beta(2), & S=\hbar, & S_{z}=-\hbar . \\
\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}[\alpha(1) \beta(2)-\beta(1) \alpha(2)], & S=0, & S_{z}=0 .
\end{array}
$$The energy released in the annihilation process mostly comes from the rest masses of the electron and positron, $\Delta E=2 m_{e} c^{2}=1.02 \mathrm{MeV}$. The released angular momentum depends on the state of the positronium before the annihilation. For the ground state $S=0$, no angular momentum is released. For the state $S=\hbar$, the angular momentum released is $\Delta J=\sqrt{l(l+1)} \hbar=\sqrt{2} \hbar$. There must be at least two photons in the final state of an annihilation, for if there were only one photon produced in the annihilation of a positronium, the energy and momentum of the system could not both be conserved. This can be shown by a simple argument. If the single photon has energy $E$, it must have a momentum $E / c$ at the same time. Thus the momentum of the photon cannot be zero in any reference frame. But in the positronium's rest frame the momentum is zero throughout the annihilation. Hence we have to conclude that there must be at least two photons in the final state of an annihilation whose momenta cancel out in the rest frame of the positronium.

3017.c.Solution:
In the $\sigma_{z}$ representation, the spin wave function is $\left(\begin{array}{l}1 \\ 0\end{array}\right)$, the eigenfunctions of $\sigma_{x}$ are $\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(\begin{array}{l}1 \\ 1\end{array}\right), \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\left(\begin{array}{r}1 \\ -1\end{array}\right)$, corresponding to eigenvalues $+1,-1$ respectively. Expanding $\left(\begin{array}{l}1 \\ 0\end{array}\right)$ in these two states, we see that the possible results of a measurement of $s_{x}$ are $\pm \hbar / 2$ since $\hat{s}_{x}=\frac{1}{2} \sigma_{x}$, the mean value being zero:

$$
\left\langle s_{x}\right\rangle=(1,0) \hat{s}_{x}\left(\begin{array}{l}
1 \\
0
\end{array}\right)=0 .
$$

The probabilities of finding the result to be $+\frac{\hbar}{2}$ and $-\frac{\hbar}{2}$ are $P_{+}$and $P_{-}$respectively:

$$
\begin{aligned}
&P_{+}=\left|\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}(1,1)\left(\begin{array}{l}
1 \\
0
\end{array}\right)\right|^{2}=\frac{1}{2}, \\
&P_{-}=\left|\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}(1,-1)\left(\begin{array}{l}
1 \\
0
\end{array}\right)\right|^{2}=\frac{1}{2} .
\end{aligned}
$$Suppose the spin axis is $\mathbf{n}=\mathbf{n}(\theta, \varphi)=.(\sin \theta \cos \varphi, \sin \theta \sin \varphi$, $\cos \theta)$. Then the eigenstates for $s_{n}=\mathbf{s} \cdot \mathbf{n}$ are

$$
\left(\begin{array}{c}
\cos \frac{\theta}{2} e^{-i \varphi / 2} \\
\sin \frac{\theta}{2} e^{i \varphi / 2}
\end{array}\right),\left(\begin{array}{c}
-\sin \frac{\theta}{2} e^{-i \varphi / 2} \\
\cos \frac{\theta}{2} e^{i \varphi / 2}
\end{array}\right),
$$

corresponding to eigenvalues $+\hbar / 2$ and $-\hbar / 2$ respectively. The probability of finding the eigenvalues $+\hbar / 2$ and $-\hbar / 2$ are $\cos ^{2}(\theta / 2)$ and $\sin ^{2}(\theta / 2)$ respectively.

3045.a.Solution:
In the representation of $s_{z}$, the eigenvectors of $s_{z^{\prime}}$ are

$$
\left(\begin{array}{c}
\cos \frac{\theta}{2} \\
\sin \frac{\theta}{2}
\end{array}\right),\left(\begin{array}{c}
-\sin \frac{\theta}{2} \\
\cos \frac{\theta}{2}
\end{array}\right),
$$

corresponding to the eigenvalues $s_{z^{\prime}}=1 / 2$ and $-1 / 2$ respectively. Then the probability amplitudes for $m^{\prime}=\pm 1 / 2$ are respectively 

$$
\begin{aligned}
&C_{+}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\cos \frac{\theta}{2} & \sin \frac{\theta}{2}
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{l}
1 \\
0
\end{array}\right)=\cos \frac{\theta}{2}, \\
&C_{-}=\left(\begin{array}{ll}
-\sin \frac{\theta}{2} & \cos \frac{\theta}{2}
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{l}
1 \\
0
\end{array}\right)=-\sin \frac{\theta}{2} .
\end{aligned}
$$

3045.b.Solution:
In the representation of $s_{z}$, the eigenvectors of $s_{z^{\prime}}$ are

$$
\left(\begin{array}{c}
\cos \frac{\theta}{2} \\
\sin \frac{\theta}{2}
\end{array}\right),\left(\begin{array}{c}
-\sin \frac{\theta}{2} \\
\cos \frac{\theta}{2}
\end{array}\right),
$$

corresponding to the eigenvalues $s_{z^{\prime}}=1 / 2$ and $-1 / 2$ respectively. Then the probability amplitudes for $m^{\prime}=\pm 1 / 2$ are respectively 

$$
\begin{aligned}
&C_{+}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\cos \frac{\theta}{2} & \sin \frac{\theta}{2}
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{l}
1 \\
0
\end{array}\right)=\cos \frac{\theta}{2}, \\
&C_{-}=\left(\begin{array}{ll}
-\sin \frac{\theta}{2} & \cos \frac{\theta}{2}
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{l}
1 \\
0
\end{array}\right)=-\sin \frac{\theta}{2} .
\end{aligned}
$$The Hamiltonian in the interval $0<t<T$ is

$$
\begin{aligned}
H &=-\mu \cdot \mathbf{B}=-\mu_{0}\left(B_{0} \sigma_{z}+B_{1} \sigma_{x}\right) \\
&=-\mu_{0}\left(\begin{array}{rr}
B_{0} & B_{1} \\
B_{1} & -B_{0}
\end{array}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

The initial eigenfunctions are

$$
\chi_{+}(0)=\left(\begin{array}{c}
\cos \frac{\theta}{2} \\
\sin \frac{\theta}{2}
\end{array}\right), \quad \chi_{-}(0)=\left(\begin{array}{c}
-\sin \frac{\theta}{2} \\
\cos \frac{\theta}{2}
\end{array}\right)
$$

where

$$
\theta=\tan ^{-1}\left(\frac{B_{1}}{B_{0}}\right) .
$$

Substitution in the Schrödinger equation $H \chi_{\pm}(0)=\pm E \chi_{\pm}(0)$ gives

$$
E=-\mu_{0} B_{0} / \cos \theta=-\mu_{0} B,
$$

where

$$
B=\sqrt{B_{0}^{2}+B_{1}^{2}} .
$$

At a later time $t$ in $0<t<T$, the eigenstates are

$$
\chi_{\pm}(t)=\exp (\mp i E t / \hbar) \chi_{\pm}(0)=\exp \left(\pm i \mu_{0} B t / \hbar\right) \chi_{\pm}(0)
$$

